# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-f-kettering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:charles-f-kettering/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with a household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona, Hong Kong, China, Japan, and Italy.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Additionally, costs concerning health care can act as another barrier, as the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia, was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The 2nd-century Chinese inventor Ding Huan of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning, particularly in the nations of Europe, where the technology is relatively unadopted.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-conditioning] The strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Bovik received a Primetime Emmy Award in 2015 for his development of perception-based video quality measurement tools that are now standards in television production.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Al Bovik was educated at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (PhD 1984).
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He has made numerous fundamental contributions to the fields of digital photography, digital television, digital image processing, digital video processing, digital cinema, and computational visual perception.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He is particularly well known for his work on low-level vision, natural scene modeling, image quality, and video quality.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He has published more than 1000 technical articles, books, and patents in these areas.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Overall, his work has been cited in the scientific and engineering literature more than 200,000 times according to Google Scholar.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He is one of the most highly cited engineers in the world according to the Web of Science.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Bovik is an elected member of the United States National Academy of Engineering (NAE), an elected Foreign Fellow of the Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE), an elected Fellow of the U.S.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] National Academy of Inventors, and an elected foreign member of Academia Europaea (2023).
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He is also a Life Fellow of the IEEE, a Fellow of Optica and of the Society of Photo-Optical and Instrumentation Engineers (SPIE), an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society (HonFRPS) and an Honorary Member of the Society for Imaging Science and Technology (IS&T).
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He is a voting member of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (Television Academy) and was named an inaugural member of its Science and Technology Peer Group.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in 2008.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] His high-dynamic range (HDR) add-on model HDRMAX, which improves the quality prediction performance of leading models is marketed and used worldwide.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He was the founder and First General Chair of the IEEE International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP).
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] He also co-founded (with David Munson, Jr.) the IEEE Transactions on Image Processing and was its longest-serving Editor-in-Chief, with a tenure of six years.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Bovik's academic legacy includes serving as the supervising professor of more than 70 PhD graduates, more than 50 master's degree recipients, and more than two dozen post-doctoral researchers.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] His award-winning online courseware is used internationally: SIVA – Courseware for Signal, Image, Video and Audio Processing.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] This online courseware offers online curricula for digital image and video processing and digital signal processing.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] SIVA includes hundreds of signal, image and video processing demonstrations delivering live, interactive audio-visual experiences of signal and image processing algorithms.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-bovik] Bovik has received a number of major international awards.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:charles-f-kettering/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:charles-f-kettering/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:charles-f-kettering/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:charles-f-kettering/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:charles-f-kettering/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Charles was born in Loudonville, Ohio, United States, the fourth of five children of Jacob Henry Kettering and Martha (Hunter) Kettering.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Poor eyesight gave him headaches in school.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] After graduation he followed his sister Emma into a teaching position at Bunker Hill School.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] By all accounts he was an engaging and innovative teacher.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He attracted students to evening scientific demonstrations on electricity, heat, magnetism, and gravity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He took classes at the College of Wooster, before transferring to Ohio State University.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He was a member of the Delta Upsilon fraternity.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Eye problems forced him to withdraw, and he took a job as foreman of a telephone line crew.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] At first, the termination of his studies caused him to be depressed.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Then he found ways to apply his electrical engineering skills on the job, and his spirits revived.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He also met his future wife, Olive Williams.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] When his eye condition improved, he was able to return to his studies and graduated from OSU in 1904 with an electrical engineering degree.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering was hired directly out of school to head the research laboratory at National Cash Register (later known as NCR Corporation).
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering invented an easy credit approval system, a precursor to today's credit cards, and the electric cash register in 1906, which made ringing up sales physically much easier for sales clerks.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering distinguished himself as a practical inventor.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] As he said, "I didn't hang around much with other inventors and the executive fellows.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] They had some real notion of what people wanted." During his five years at NCR, from 1904 to 1909, Kettering secured 23 patents for NCR.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Beginning in 1907, his NCR colleague Edward A.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Deeds convinced Kettering to develop improvements for the automobile.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Deeds and Kettering invited other NCR engineers, including Harold E.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Talbott, to join them nights and weekends in their tinkering at Deeds's barn.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] They became known as the "Barn Gang," and Kettering was called Boss Ket.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Their first goal was to find a replacement for the magneto.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1909, Kettering resigned from NCR to work full-time on automotive developments, and the group incorporated as Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company, or Delco.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The hand crank used to start early automobiles could kick back under some circumstances.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Byron Carter, founder of Cartercar, died from complications after such an accident in Detroit's Belle Isle park.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Leland – the head of Cadillac – became determined to develop an electric self-starting device.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] When Leland's engineers failed to develop a self-starter small enough to be practical he consulted Kettering, and Delco developed a practical model by February 1911.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering's key insight lay in devising an electrical system performing the three functions it still serves in modern cars: starter; producer of spark for ignition; and source of current for lighting.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Leland ordered 12,000 self-starters for his 1912 models; Delco had to then transition from its research and development activities to production.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The invention won a Dewar Trophy in 1913.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering helped found the Engineers Club of Dayton in 1914.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1914, Flxible Sidecar Company was incorporated with the help of Kettering, who then became president of the company and joined the board of directors.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering provided significant funding for the company in its early years, particularly after 1916, when Kettering sold his firm, the Dayton Engineering Laboratories Company (Delco), to United Motors Company for $2.5 million.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering continued to serve as president of Flxible until he became chairman of the board in 1940, a position that he held until his death in 1958.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Delco was sold to General Motors in 1918, as part of United Motors.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Delco became the foundation for the General Motors Research Corporation and Delco Electronics.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering became vice-president of General Motors Research Corporation in 1920 and held the position for 27 years.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Between 1918 and 1923, he led the research and development at GM's Dayton research laboratories to commercialize air-cooled engines for cars and trucks.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The GM "copper-cooled" automotive engine used fans forcing air across copper fins for heat dissipation.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The commercialization, attempted between 1921 and 1923, was unsuccessful due to a combination of factors, nontechnical and technical.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Air-cooled engines have had commercial success before and since, used widely in such applications as lawnmowers, small aircraft, and automobiles - notably the Volkswagen Beetle and many generations of Porsche sports cars.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering's research in fuel was based on his belief that oil would be in short supply and additives would allow more efficient engines with higher compression.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] His "high percentage" solution was to mix ethanol with gasoline, while his "low percentage solution" looked for additives that would be added in small quantities to increase what later would be called the octane rating of gasoline.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Thomas Midgley Jr. and Kettering identified tetraethyllead (TEL) in December 1921 as an additive that would eliminate engine knocking at a dilution of one thousand to one.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] While use of ethanol could not be patented, TEL's use as an additive could.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering and Midgley secured its patent and proceeded to promote the use of TEL as an additive instead of other options.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering became the first president of the newly founded Ethyl Corporation that started to produce TEL in 1923.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kehoe as the medical expert to proclaim that leaded gasoline was safe for humans.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] That its use was an ecological disaster leading to a global lead contamination was not acknowledged until many decades later.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering married Olive Williams of Ashland, Ohio, on August 1, 1905.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Their only child, Eugene Williams Kettering, was born on April 20, 1908.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Eugene joined Winton Engine in 1930, which was acquired by General Motors and was eventually incorporated into the General Motors Electro-Motive Division (EMD).
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He became a central figure in the development of the EMD 567 locomotive engine and the Detroit Diesel 6-71 engine, serving at EMD until his retirement in 1960.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Charles Kettering built a house, "Ridgeleigh Terrace", in 1914.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] According to local sources, it was the first in the United States to have electric air conditioning using freon.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Ridgeleigh Terrace was the home of his son, Eugene, until his death.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Eugene's wife, Virginia, lived in the house for many years, restoring and redecorating it.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In the late 1990s, the house largely destroyed in a fire, and was rebuilt with serious deviation from the original blueprints to accommodate its current use as a conference center.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Some of Charles' memorable quotations are: "It doesn't matter if you try and try and try again, and fail.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] It does matter if you try and fail, and fail to try again.", "Failures are finger posts on the road to achievement.", "My interest is in the future because I am going to spend the rest of my life there." .
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] After his death, his body lay in honor at the Engineers Club and then was interred in the mausoleum at Woodland Cemetery, Dayton, Ohio.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering and Deeds had a lifelong business, professional and personal relationship.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1914, recognizing that Dayton was among the leading industrial cities in the US because of the skilled engineers and technicians in the city, they founded the Engineers Club of Dayton and the Foreman's Club of Dayton, which later on became the National Management Association.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He invented the all-electric starting, ignition, and lighting system for automobiles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Electric starters replaced crank (manual) starting of automobiles.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] First incorporated in the 1912 Cadillac, all-electric starting aided in the growth of the US auto industry by making the automobile easy for anyone to start.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Other patents included a portable lighting system and an incubator for premature infants.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] His engine-driven generator was combined with storage batteries to form a "Delco Plant", providing electrical power for farmsteads and other locations far from the power grid.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1918 Kettering designed the "aerial torpedo", nicknamed the Kettering Bug.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering and colleagues' development of leaded gasoline ultimately caused the release of large quantities of lead into the atmosphere as a result of the combustion of leaded gasoline all over the world.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Due to the neurotoxic effects of lead, leaded gasoline has been widely banned since the late 1990s.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The development of Freon using CFCs has been implicated in the depletion of the ozone layer.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He developed the idea of Duco paint and helped develop diesel engines and ways to harness solar energy.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] He was a pioneer in the application of magnetism to medical diagnostic techniques.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] His inventions, especially the electric automobile starter, made him wealthy.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1945, he helped found what became the Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, based on the premise that American industrial research techniques could be applied to cancer research..
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] His son and daughter-in-law, Eugene and Virginia, created Kettering Medical Center in Ohio, as a tribute to Charles Kettering's life and his work in healthcare research.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] On January 1, 1998, the former General Motors Institute changed its name to Kettering University to honor Kettering as a founder.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] In 1998, GMI Engineering and Management Institute (formerly General Motors Institute), of Flint, Michigan, changed its name to Kettering University in honor of Kettering.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] His ideals, prowess, and belief in co-operative education continue there.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering is also remembered through the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, a cancer research and treatment center in New York City, and through the Kettering Health Network, which includes several hospitals and medical center campuses as well as Kettering College in Kettering, Ohio.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The city of Kettering, Ohio, a suburb of Dayton, was named after him when it was incorporated in 1955.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Army Air Service testing field, McCook Field, is now a Dayton park called Kettering Field.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The endowed Olive Williams Kettering Chair of The College of Wooster Department of Music is named in honor of his wife.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The University of Dayton's engineering building, Kettering Labs, is named after him.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] The Kettering Science center on the Ashland University campus in Ohio is named for him.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering Hall at Wilmington College is named for him, also *Kettering Hall of Science* at Oberlin College.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] At Antioch College, the 1929 Science Building he donated was not named after him (it is now the Arts and Science Building), but the school's 33.000-square-foot Charles F.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Kettering Building was (the same being originally a research facility, now home to campus radio station WYSO), while the college's Olive Kettering Library was named after his wife.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Electric driving device for registering-machines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Driving mechanism for registering-machines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Engine starting, lighting, and ignition system.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] System of selective electrical distribution.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Driving device for registering-machines.
[src:charles-f-kettering/charles-f-kettering] Ignition apparatus for explosion-motors.
